Crusader of Brell</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=soulflayerdwagonslayer>Soulflayer Dwagonslayer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 5:29:29 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Improve or not the warriors?</span><hr size=1> As to my regards to AC items. The Elemental Armor was never really in question, but when you look for Rings, Earrings, Belts, Shoulders, Masks and Range Slot items you will find the AC leaves alot to be desired. I agree that non plate classes shouldn't get high AC to the point like Velious and SoL gave them but if you look at the warrior only items they are lacking in AC. The best warrior shoulders in PoP are 25 AC, while there are several shoulders with much better AC for far less risk from older expansions. In many cases VT items won't be replaces due to them have a stellar Stats, AC, Saves and Effects which can't be made up for infinetly harder item to obtain, for a measly 20 more hp or 20 more mana with a huge loss of AC and saves.<br>
<br>
<br>
[b]Graal the Dwarf[/b]<br>
<br>
[quote]I actually think that is a good idea, with one caveat: there has to be a time penalty to switching between the different modes. Make it take 20 seconds to switch, or make it so you can only switch once every 3 minutes, or something.[/quote]<br>
<br>
There needs to be actually no time penalty for doing this, otherwise warriors are back to square one. The proposed plan of shifting your attack type should happen at the users discretion and instantly. Any weapons masters can go from all out attack, or to a basic stance ( normal ), to a very evassive stance, or to a very defensive stance at a moments notice,  thus there is no reason to have a penalty for doing.<br>
<br>
The penalty already comes into play when you enter the stance. Defensive was you take 30 to 40% less damage while you deal out 30 to 40% less damage. Evassive is you get hit less yet you hit for less as well. Aggressive is you deal 20 to 30% more damage yet you get hit for 20 to 30% more. Aggressive would give warriors a higher DPS but they have to open themsleves up to do so. Hell when you are fighting mobs in the Elemental Planes that Quad + Flurry over 2k, how long would a warrior last with 9k HP in Aggressive? Or Scale this example down to a tank who is 6k HP vs AoW who Quads for 1000ish + Flurry. Or would you go aggressive vs mobs who AE rampage? That MT dies or you get turned on just once you are paste if your in aggressive. <br>
<br>
<br>
Warriors need a real advantage for people to consider when choosing which class they want for their party make up, and since the Warrior comes with no utility and most XP group rarely if ever require them to use a Discipline likes Evassive or Defensive, what does that leave the warrior to offer? 10% more damage then a Paly/SK and where everyone has to wear baby gloves on letting the warrior get agro, thus slowing down the group, thus slowing down xp, not to mention ping ponging causes more mana from the healers which equals more down time.<br>
<br>
Imagine a Chanter, Shaman and Cleric, sitting in a PoP zone where the mobs hit for 500 to 900ish triple attack. They are forming a xp group to work on AA pts. They do a /who LFG and here is what they see.<br>
<br>
65 Paladin LFG<br>
65 Warrior LFG<br>
65 Monk LFG<br>
65 Rogue LFG<br>
65 SK LFG<br>
65 Ranger LFG.<br>
<br>
Which would they choose? More then likely they would go with Paladin to tank, Monk to pull, and Rogue for serious DPS or Ranger for serious DPS + Utility buffs + Snare.<br>
<br>
Lets take another example where a Cleric, Bard, Shaman, Rogue, Rogue are looking for last member to fill a spot in the same type of XP zone as mentioned in previous example. They do a /who LFG and here is what they see.<br>
<br>
65 Warrior LFG<br>
65 Paladin LFG <br>
65 SK LFG<br>
<br>
Which class would they choose as their Tank Class? Since I have 65 Cleric with Divine Arbitration I would go with the Paladin for Wave of Prexus or Marr, not mention BMB or BSS, and superior agro control with stuns and heals.. Some would probably go with SK for the Feign Pulling Ability. <br>
<br>
<br>
Yet both classes mentioned were above the warrior. Why? The warrior offers nothing to the group. 500 more hitpoints is one extra swing with the down side of not being able to command agro at will. Even with 2 EB weapons they are waiting for procs, which during this time the party is put on sharp glass on how they manage their agro. If the warrior opens with a proc or two life is good, if not they go for AE taunt ( 15 minutes or 10.5 with AA ) or they stand and watch the party die.<br>
<br>
If you add the proposed slider bar, the warrior become much more attractive, though it doesn't completely cure the warrior but goes a long way in doing so. Now a party would have to consider this.<br>
<br>
1) Warrior while haveing a slight hit point to help keep them alive, can now mitigate full time better then any class hands down. This alone would make them attractive to healing classes. Aggressive would allow a 2nd Warrior in group to contribute much more DPS even if they do so at a reckless pace, and will be forced to carefully balance his agro.The Second Warrior can switch in to tank mode should the Primary Tank die. Note that warriors can AE taunt and /shield should the going get rough.<br>
<br>
2) Paladins while doing slightly less DPS then warrior, will have supreme agro control. Not only that, but with high level stuns, they to can mitigate damage or buy time for that CH. Healing Wave series of spells can be augmented for over 2K crits. The group heal not only heals efficently but is also a great AE taunt. Need to save someone on the fly then Lay of Hands does just that or maybe toss in a root to hold off an add. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Bottom line is Verant did some stellar work in rounding off the Paladin into a very exciting and playable class from what it used to be. Warriors needs some serious overhauling as the class is only living off of 2 Discipline Skills that they recieved at level 52 and 55 and even those are restricted to by time. So for 3 minutes out of 7 minutes for Evassive and 10 minutes for Defensive does the warrior mitigate damage better then a hybrid and even then Warriors only shine vs mobs that hit for over 2K and is impossible to keep a heal cycle on w/o them dieing, those mobs are far and few. At the current rate your guild might be asking Warriors to get a good shield, max out your /shield Discipline to 48 Seconds and get into a shielding order to keep the Paladin or SK alive vs the boss mobs.<br>
